derivation.yuyuan_name: Middle English (in the sense 'excellence'): from Latin excellentia, from excellere 'surpass' (see excel). The use of the word as a title dates from the mid 16th cent

entry.def: You use expressions such as Your Excellency or His Excellency when you are addressing or referring to officials of very high rank, for example ambassadors or governors.

example.ex: I am reluctant to trust anyone totally, Your Excellency...
example.tran: 我不想完全相信任何人，阁下。

example.ex: His excellency the President will be waiting for you in the hall.
example.tran: 总统阁下会在大厅等你。

means.word_mean: 1. a title used to address dignitaries (such as ambassadors or governors); usually preceded by Your or His or Her;
